 {"id":"frankentorch-dp7","title":"Audit and harden feature-gated code paths for completeness","description":"## Context
The stub/placeholder audit (2026-04-02) found two feature-gated functions in ft-runtime/src/lib.rs:

1. `#[cfg(feature = "asupersync-integration")] pub fn asupersync_infinite_budget()` (line ~167)
2. `#[cfg(feature = "frankentui-integration")] pub fn frankentui_default_style()` (line ~172)

Both are thin wrappers delegating to external crate defaults. They work correctly but lack doc comments and have no tests.

Workspace Cargo.toml confirms both dependencies are available:
- `asupersync = { version = "0.2.0" }`
- `ftui = { version = "0.2.0" }`

So feature-gated tests CAN be run in this workspace.

## Plan

### Step 1: Add doc comments to both functions
```rust
/// Returns an infinite budget for asupersync structured concurrency regions.
///
/// Use this when FrankenTorch operations should not be time-bounded by the
/// runtime's cancel budget — for example, during offline inference or
/// non-interactive batch processing.
///
/// Requires the `asupersync-integration` feature flag.
#[cfg(feature = "asupersync-integration")]
pub fn asupersync_infinite_budget() -> asupersync::types::Budget {
    asupersync::types::Budget::INFINITE
}
```

```rust
/// Returns the default TUI rendering style for FrankenTorch dashboard panels.
///
/// This provides a baseline style that can be customized by the consumer.
/// Used by the optional TUI dashboard integration.
///
/// Requires the `frankentui-integration` feature flag.
#[cfg(feature = "frankentui-integration")]
pub fn frankentui_default_style() -> ftui::Style {
    ftui::Style::default()
}
```

### Step 2: Add feature-gated tests in the existing test module
```rust
#[cfg(feature = "asupersync-integration")]
#[test]
fn asupersync_infinite_budget_returns_infinite() {
    // Verify the function compiles and returns a value.
    // Budget::INFINITE is a const, so this mainly guards against
    // API drift in the asupersync crate.
    let _budget = super::asupersync_infinite_budget();
}

#[cfg(feature = "frankentui-integration")]
#[test]
fn frankentui_default_style_returns_valid_style() {
    // Verify the function compiles and returns a value.
    // Style::default() is a std trait, so this guards against
    // ftui removing the Default impl.
    let _style = super::frankentui_default_style();
}
```

### Step 3: Add a comment documenting how to test
In the test module, add:
```rust
// Feature-gated integration tests. Run with:
//   cargo test -p ft-runtime --features asupersync-integration
//   cargo test -p ft-runtime --features frankentui-integration
//   cargo test -p ft-runtime --all-features
```

## Testing requirements

### Default (no features)
- `rch exec -- cargo test -p ft-runtime` — existing tests pass
- `rch exec -- cargo clippy -p ft-runtime -- -D warnings` — clean
- `rch exec -- cargo doc -p ft-runtime --no-deps` — zero warnings

### With features
- `rch exec -- cargo test -p ft-runtime --features asupersync-integration` — new test passes
- `rch exec -- cargo test -p ft-runtime --features frankentui-integration` — new test passes
- `rch exec -- cargo test -p ft-runtime --all-features` — all tests pass

### Full workspace sanity
- `rch exec -- cargo check --workspace` — no breakage from doc comments

## Acceptance Criteria
- Both functions have doc comments with purpose, usage context, and feature-flag requirement
- 2 feature-gated tests exist and pass when features enabled
- Default (no-feature) build unchanged
- cargo doc clean

